fields.value:
Welcome to PYANO Admin project!

Introduction

PYthon ANnOtation (PYANO) framework is a one-to-many model oriented annotation tool, where a sinlge project owner can build and call for participants from many workers all over the world. While PYANO has been limited to only a single project owner, PYANO admin supports multiple project owners and still in development stage. With the design of a many-to-many models in mind, we are working toward building a customizable annotation tools which can increase the automation degree of conventional data collection and annotation processes which are often tedious and manual.

Basic of PYANO

PYANO supports a spatial-temporal annotation pipeline with human involved, therefore, it is a semi-automatic annotation tool. In the latest version, PYANO has been almost in beta version, which is close to a public distribution. While most features of PYANO came to be mature, it is the time to summarize the annotation pipelines which are supported in PYANO. The source code of PYANO can be obtained freely under a MIT license (https://github.com/mental689/pyano).

In general, a spatio-temporal annotation pipeline by PYANO and PYANO-admin consists of three major steps: 

  • Keyword based search: This is a first step to collect dataset from Internet sources such as YouTube. After a worker enter a keyword or a set of keywords, PYANO will contact YouTube to obtain a list of relevant videos using YouTube Data API v3. This step is semi-automatic, with the only human labor force is for entering keywords. Human labors will be asked by project owners to come up with relevant keywords to a given topic (for example, in the demo of PYANO, we use 'shoplifting' as the initial topic). Usually, the project owners have to conduct such an experiment with human subjects to collect an appropriate video sets (irrelevant keywords can lead to an inappropriate video set). Although, PYANO helps project owners to do well with YouTube API stuffs, it helps almost nothing in automating the coming up with keywords processes. PYANO-admin have been developed to resolve this drawback of PYANO. The major obstacle is that PYANO relies on only one project owner for each project, while having multiple project owners often increase the participations.
  • Web-based surveys: In the second step, after videos have been searched and added to the database, the project owners often discover that there are many irrelevant (negative) videos in collected YouTube videos. It is an issue of search engine and PYANO cannot modify Google YouTube's engine! To support project owners to further filter negative videos, PYANO use web-based questionnaires which have a trade-off between cost and answer rate. Other interview technologies (face-to-face and video conference softwares) may increase the answer rates but the cost to setup a meeting is often high! Email-based methods have low answer rates but it is much cheaper. To combine all advantages of these methods, PYANO has started with web-based questionnaires with an email-based call-for-participant process to trade-off between cost and answer rate. Future development of PYANO and PYANO-admin would contain a plugin for video conferencing and web chat app to have more options for projetc owners to gain participants. For current web-based solutions, PYANO have a serious problem with a single project owner: that is similar to Keyword based search, the answer rate can be lower without multiple project owners. All of what project owners have to do in this step is to coming up with a survey that can filter as many as possible negatives, then the annotators in next space-time annotation step can focus only in positive videos.
  • Semi-automatic space-time annotations: We use a semi-automatic annotation tool, VATIC: Video Annotation Tool from Irvine, California. After surveys' results have been collected and the project owners felt that the results are reliable to choose videos to go to space-time annotation step, PYANO will automate the step of downloading the videos to preparing the annotation tool VATIC. PYANO also help to visualize the survey results and the video in a single page, then the project owner can have more confidence while making decisions. Project owners will go to review pages to select video to be annotated in space-time step, and pusing download button to finish all what they have to do. If the project owners don't want to do this step, they can outsource this task to outside reviewers who want to work. Of course, project owners have to decide the price for each task to pay for annotator and reviewer.

PYANO has been developed to help project owners who do not have sufficient computer skills to do a space-time annotation project using crowd sourcing workers. Our goal is to distribute a semi-automatic tool, where the researcher without computer skills can finish their data collection pipeline with the focus on their own tasks.

However, as stated above, PYANO still has some gaps when handling multi-owner projects, as it does not fully use the advantages multiple owners can bring into research. This is the major motivation for us to develop and study about PYANO-admin.

fields.name: Shoplifting
fields.description: Shoplifting is the act of knowingly taking goods from an establishment in which they are displayed for sale, without paying for them.

fields.name: Build a dataset for shoplifting prevention

fields.guideline:
Thank you for joining our experiment! 
In this experiment, you will be asked to watch a video from start to its ending, then please answer a set of questions at the bottom of this page. 
Please do not hesitate to contact to us for further questions regarding to this experiment.

  • Definition

Shoplifting is the act of knowingly taking goods from an establishment in which they are displayed for sale, without paying for them.

  • Requirements

The above definition is taken from Wikipedia. It is easy to observe three important aspects of a shoplifting scene:

  • Activity: Shoplifting is an acitivity of taking something from someone or organizations.
  • Goods and shops: There must be goods which are displayed for sale in a shop (indoor or maybe outdoor in some cases).
  • No payment: The good is taken by a person from a shop without any payment. (Note that, it is OK to watching and checking the good many times, but finally making a payment. For e.g., a man who watching many goods inside the shop for 3 hours and then making a payment and obtaining a bill is NOT shoplifting. But if a man take some goods after one or two minutes, go out without paying money, there is a high probability that it is shoplifting.)

Although the above definition is strict, in practice, we may want to notice the criminals as soon as the sign of crimes appear. Therefore, some common senses can be used when you find that the above conditions are unclear to judge a crime, such as:

  • Suspicious activities: it is unusual for a person to put a good that he/she has not paid for, into his/her pocket. This situation should be put in an alarm. Justice force will decide whether to put a further investigation on the target.
  • Prank, movies, unnatural scenes: In the social networks and video sharing sites, it is usual to observe many scenes which look real but after a further investigation, it turns out that those videos are pranks. Please do not worry about those at this stage, we will ask other professionals to put their effort in further investigations.

When you find that your are in a situation which is difficult to make decisions about the crimes, please check the video as "Not Sure" and put your comments about why you were hesitating in the textbox of the final question. Some other notes:

  • Do not mark the stealing in game videos or surreal videos as positive.
  • A scene with violence but without clear evidences of shoplifting should not be checked as positive.

For a training before watching the videos, please watch the following examples:

  • Positive (shoplifting events): P1, P2
  • Negative (no shoplifting): N1, N2, N3
